# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: decal-rendering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] In computer graphics, **alpha compositing** or **alpha blending** is the process of combining one image with a background to create the appearance of partial or full transparency.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] It is often useful to render picture elements (pixels) in separate passes or layers and then combine the resulting 2D images into a single, final image called the composite.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] Compositing is used extensively in film when combining computer-rendered image elements with live footage.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] Alpha blending is also used in 2D computer graphics to put rasterized foreground elements over a background.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] In order to combine the picture elements of the images correctly, it is necessary to keep an associated *matte* for each element in addition to its color.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] This matte layer contains the coverage information—the shape of the geometry being drawn—making it possible to distinguish between parts of the image where something was drawn and parts that are empty.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] Although the most basic operation of combining two images is to put one over the other, there are many operations, or blend modes, that are used.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] The concept of an alpha channel was introduced by Alvy Ray Smith and Ed Catmull in the late 1970s at the New York Institute of Technology Computer Graphics Lab.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] Wallace derived the same straight **over** operator based on a physical reflectance/transmittance model in 1981.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] A 1984 paper by Thomas Porter and Tom Duff introduced premultiplied alpha using a geometrical approach.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] The use of the term *alpha* is explained by Smith as follows: "We called it that because of the classic linear interpolation formula $\alpha A+(1-\alpha )B$ that uses the Greek letter $\alpha$ (alpha) to control the amount of interpolation between, in this case, two images A and B".
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] That is, when compositing image A atop image B, the value of $\alpha$ in the formula is taken directly from A's alpha channel.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] In a 2D image a color combination is stored for each picture element (pixel), often a combination of red, green and blue (RGB).
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] When alpha compositing is in use, each pixel has an additional numeric value stored in its **alpha channel**, with a value ranging from 0 to 1.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] A value of 0 means that the pixel is fully transparent and the color in the pixel beneath will show through.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] A value of 1 means that the pixel is fully opaque.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] With the existence of an alpha channel, it is possible to express compositing image operations using a *compositing algebra*.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] For example, given two images *A* and *B*, the most common compositing operation is to combine the images so that *A* appears in the foreground and *B* appears in the background.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] This can be expressed as *A* **over** *B*.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] The **over** operator is, in effect, the normal painting operation (see Painter's algorithm).
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] The **in** and **out** operators are the alpha compositing equivalent of clipping.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] The two use only the alpha channel of the second image and ignore the color components.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] In addition, **plus** defines additive blending.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] If an alpha channel is used in an image, there are two common representations that are available: straight (unassociated) alpha and premultiplied (associated) alpha.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] The most significant advantage of premultiplied alpha is that it allows for correct blending, interpolation, and filtering.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] Ordinary interpolation without premultiplied alpha leads to RGB information leaking out of fully transparent (A=0) regions, even though this RGB information is ideally invisible.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] When interpolating or filtering images with abrupt borders between transparent and opaque regions, this can result in borders of colors that were not visible in the original image.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] Errors also occur in areas of semitransparency because the RGB components are not correctly weighted, giving incorrectly high weighting to the color of the more transparent (lower alpha) pixels.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] Premultiplied alpha may also be used to allow regions of regular alpha blending (e.g. smoke) and regions with additive blending mode (e.g. flame and glitter effects) to be encoded within the same image.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] This is represented by an RGBA triplet that express emission with no occlusion, such as (0.4, 0.3, 0.2, 0.0).
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] Another advantage of premultiplied alpha is performance; in certain situations, it can reduce the number of multiplication operations (e.g. if the image is used many times during later compositing).
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] The Porter–Duff operations have a simple form only in premultiplied alpha.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] Some rendering pipelines expose a "straight alpha" API surface, but converts them into premultiplied alpha for performance.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] One disadvantage of premultiplied alpha is that it can reduce the available relative precision in the RGB values when using integer or fixed-point representation for the color components.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] This may cause a noticeable loss of quality if the color information is later brightened or if the alpha channel is removed.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] In practice, this is not usually noticeable because during typical composition operations, such as OVER, the influence of the low-precision color information in low-alpha areas on the final output image (after composition) is correspondingly reduced.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] This loss of precision also makes premultiplied images easier to compress using certain compression schemes, as they do not record the color variations hidden inside transparent regions, and can allocate fewer bits to encode low-alpha areas.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] The same “limitations” of lower quantisation bit depths such as 8 bit per channel are also present in imagery without alpha, and this argument is problematic as a result.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] Assuming that the pixel color is expressed using *straight* (non-premultiplied) RGBA tuples, a pixel value of (0, 0.7, 0, 0.5) implies a pixel that has 70% of the maximum green intensity and 50% opacity.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] If the color were fully green, its RGBA would be (0, 1, 0, 0.5).
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] However, if this pixel uses premultiplied alpha, all of the RGB values (0, 0.7, 0) are multiplied, or scaled for occlusion, by the alpha value 0.5, which is appended to yield (0, 0.35, 0, 0.5).
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] In this case, the 0.35 value for the G channel actually indicates 70% green emission intensity (with 50% occlusion).
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] A pure green emission would be encoded as (0, 0.5, 0, 0.5).
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] Knowing whether a file uses straight or premultiplied alpha is essential to correctly process or composite it, as a different calculation is required.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] Emission with no occlusion cannot be represented in straight alpha.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] No conversion is available in this case.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] The most popular image formats that support the alpha channel are PNG and TIFF.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] GIF supports 1-bit transparency by designating one palette entry as transparent.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] Support for alpha channels is present in some video codecs, such as Animation and Apple ProRes 4444 of the QuickTime format, or in the Techsmith multi-format codec.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] This transformation better utilizes the limited number of bits in the encoded image by choosing $\gamma$ that better matches the non-linear human perception of luminance.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] When combined with premultiplied alpha, pre-multiplication is done in linear space, prior to gamma compression.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] Note that the alpha channel may or may not undergo gamma-correction, even when the color channels do.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] Although used for similar purposes, transparent colors and image masks do not permit the smooth blending of the superimposed image pixels with those of the background (only whole image pixels or whole background pixels allowed).
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] A similar effect can be achieved with a 1-bit alpha channel, as found in the 16-bit RGBA high color mode of the Truevision TGA image file format and related TARGA and AT-Vista/NU-Vista display adapters' high color graphic mode.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] This mode devotes 5 bits for every primary RGB color (15-bit RGB) plus a remaining bit as the "alpha channel".
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] Dithering can be used to simulate partial occlusion where only 1-bit alpha is available.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] For some applications, a single alpha channel is not sufficient: a stained-glass window, for instance, requires a separate transparency channel for each RGB channel to model the red, green and blue transparency separately.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] More alpha channels can be added for accurate spectral color filtration applications.
[src:decal-rendering/alpha-compositing] Some order-independent transparency methods replace the **over** operator with a commutative approximation.
[src:decal-rendering/decal] A **decal** (/ˈdiːkæl/, US also /dɪˈkæl/, CAN /ˈdɛkəl/) or **transfer** is a plastic, cloth, paper, or ceramic substrate that has a pattern or image printed on it which can be moved to another surface upon contact, usually with the aid of heat or water.
[src:decal-rendering/decal] The word is short for *decalcomania*, a decorative technique by which engravings and prints are transferred to pottery or other materials.
[src:decal-rendering/decal] The technique was invented by Simon François Ravenet (1706-1774), an engraver from France who later moved to England and perfected the process he called "décalquer" (which means "to copy by tracing"); it became widespread during the decal craze or mania of the late 19th century.
[src:decal-rendering/decal] As applied, where only the adhesive-backed artwork remains, affixed to its desired (and appropriate) substrate, temporarily or permanently as designed.
[src:decal-rendering/decal] Mass-production of vinyl decals starts with large rolls of vinyl sheet.
[src:decal-rendering/decal] Vinyl is fed through a cutting plotter or large-format printer/cutter which prints the desired image and cuts out the desired shapes.
[src:decal-rendering/decal] Designs are typically created using specialized computer software and sent to the machines electronically.
[src:decal-rendering/decal] Modern cutting systems have evolved to achieve sub-millimeter precision on die-cut decals through automated processes and sophisticated blade pressure control.
[src:decal-rendering/decal] After the patterns are cut, excess vinyl on the sheet is removed in a process called *weeding*.
[src:decal-rendering/decal] Finally, a paper pre-mask can be applied to the top of the vinyl design allowing easy application of multiple letters and shapes.
[src:decal-rendering/decal] A recent innovation involves the inclusion of a radio frequency identification (RFID) circuit (chip and antenna) in the paper or film facestock.
[src:decal-rendering/decal] Decals were popularly associated from the mid-20th century on with hot rod automobiles and plastic models.
[src:decal-rendering/decal] Along with stickers they are used to "personalize" items, such as musical instruments or sports gear.
[src:decal-rendering/decal] Government agencies (and some private-public partnerships) use permanent peel-and-stick stickers on vehicles for identification.
[src:decal-rendering/decal] These "decals" are referred to as fleet markings and are required by law on all fire and law enforcement vehicles in the US.
[src:decal-rendering/decal] Most fleet markings are created from reflective vinyl with an adhesive backing that is applied in a peel-and-stick manner.
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] In the field of 3D computer graphics, **deferred shading** is a screen-space shading technique that is performed on a second rendering pass, after the vertex and pixel shaders are rendered.
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] It was first suggested by Michael Deering in 1988.
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] On the first pass of a deferred shader, only data that is required for shading computation is gathered.
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] Positions, normals, and materials for each surface are rendered into the geometry buffer (G-buffer) using "render to texture".
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] After this, a pixel shader computes the direct and indirect lighting at each pixel using the information of the texture buffers in screen space.
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] Screen space directional occlusion can be made part of the deferred shading pipeline to give directionality to shadows and interreflections.
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] The primary advantage of deferred shading is the decoupling of scene geometry from lighting.
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] Only one geometry pass is required, and each light is only computed for those pixels that it actually affects.
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] This gives the ability to render many lights in a scene without a significant performance hit.
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] There are some other advantages claimed for the approach.
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] These include simpler management of complex lighting resources, ease of managing other complex shader resources, and the simplification of the software rendering pipeline.
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] One key disadvantage of deferred rendering is the inability to handle transparency within the algorithm, although this problem is a generic one in Z-buffered scenes and it tends to be handled by delaying and sorting the rendering of transparent portions of the scene.
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] Depth peeling can be used to achieve order-independent transparency in deferred rendering, but at the cost of additional batches and g-buffer size.
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] Modern hardware, supporting DirectX 10 and later, is often capable of performing batches fast enough to maintain interactive frame rates.
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] When order-independent transparency is desired (commonly for consumer applications) deferred shading is no less effective than forward shading using the same technique.
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] Another serious disadvantage is the difficulty with using multiple materials.
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] It's possible to use many different materials, but it requires more data to be stored in the G-buffer, which is already quite large and takes up a large amount of the memory bandwidth.
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] One more disadvantage is that, due to separating the lighting stage from the geometric stage, hardware anti-aliasing does not produce correct results anymore since interpolated subsamples would result in nonsensical position, normal, and tangent attributes.
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] Although it is not an edge-smoothing technique, temporal anti-aliasing (used in *Halo: Reach and Unreal Engine*) can also help give edges a smoother appearance.
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] DirectX 10 introduced features allowing shaders to access individual samples in multi-sampled render targets (and depth buffers in version 10.1), giving users of this API access to hardware anti-aliasing in deferred shading.
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] These features also allow them to correctly apply HDR luminance mapping to anti-aliased edges, where in earlier versions of the API any benefit of anti-aliasing may have been lost.
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] Use of the technique has increased in video games because of the control it enables in terms of using a large amount of dynamic lights and reducing the complexity of required shader instructions.
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] In comparison to deferred lighting, this technique is not very popular due to high memory size and bandwidth requirements, especially on seventh generation consoles where graphic memory size and bandwidth are limited and often bottlenecks.
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] The idea of deferred shading was originally introduced by Michael Deering and his colleagues in a paper published in 1988 titled *The triangle processor and normal vector shader: a VLSI system for high performance graphics*.
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] Although the paper never uses the word "deferred", a key concept is introduced; each pixel is shaded only once after depth resolution.
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] Deferred shading as we know it today, using G-buffers, was introduced in a paper by Saito and Takahashi in 1990, although they too do not use the word "deferred".
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] The first deferred shaded video game was *Shrek*, an Xbox launch title shipped in 2001.
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] Around 2004, implementations on commodity graphics hardware started to appear.
[src:decal-rendering/deferred-shading] The technique later gained popularity for applications such as video games, finally becoming mainstream around 2008 to 2010.
